var data =
{"type":"FeatureCollection","features":[
    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Mellow Path", "memory":"While on my way to Savery Hall, I often notice squirrels hanging about. Once, there were some students feeding the squirrels, which I had found to be most wonderful. Another time, after a night of rather stormy weather, there were quite a few squirrels that seemed to be making the most of the fallen tree debris. As I pass through this space, I often hope to be graced by the presence of a gray squirrel or two (or three, or four, and so on). The squirrels really do contribute so much joy to this space! While my memories here blend together multiple points in time, the strongest temporal associations are often with the Winter months of the past two years (2024 and 2025).",
            "time":["2023-2024", "2024-2025"], "association":["Joy", "Comfort"], "color":"#B2BEB5", "quirk":"Mellow Path", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30832013699835, 47.657583136930484],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Mellow Path", "memory":"I have come to associate this space with the memory of pondering geography colloquium sessions with a friend. We would pass through here on our way back from these sessions, and this was often the point at which our conversations would take a deeper turn as we dove into our interpretations of what had been shared. It was right here, as we neared the pedestrian bridge, that I often felt that I had made enough sense of my own thoughts on the topic to be able to offer them. Engaging with complex topics in the geography discipline, and riding the high of an intellectually stimulating session, I found myself harboring a keen sense of belonging. I felt that I belonged on the campus, in the discipline, and, most importantly, as a friend. How fortunate am I, that my friend–and, in one case, friends–joined me in the geography discipline for a moment? This is a memory of gratitude, first and foremost. Although it may be more accurate to consider this to be a blend of various memories, beginning in Winter 2024 but most frequently associated with the Spring of 2024.",
            "time":["2023-2024"], "association":["Belonging"], "color":"#4CBB17", "quirk":"Mellow Path", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30833422859311, 47.65860821238959],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Mellow Path", "memory":"Returning from an evening tea time on campus (a small event co-hosted by Tea Club and a book club), I happened to get caught up in a bit of stormy weather. It was a dark and violent night, with wind thrashing, thunder roaring, and the rain threatening to pour. The occasional screams–playful in nature, so no need to fret–rang out from across the yard as other unfortunate souls found themselves similarly exposed to such aggressive weather. I, myself, was certainly feeling anxious; the dangers of falling debris are to be taken seriously, and the stability of my trusty bucket hat was very much in question. Yet I also felt a remarkable sense of excitement, of being so immediately immersed and present in the space that I could not help but experience a strange peace in the face of such dastardly elements. It would not be much of a stretch to suggest that this experience has since enriched my relationship to this space. That one night during the Winter of 2025, after all, may be the most present I have ever felt in a space here on campus.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Joy", "Discomfort", "Uncertainty"], "color":"#191970", "quirk":"Mellow Path", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30780579381972, 47.657839407685266],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Mellow Path", "memory":"Routinely passing through–don't mind me! This is a common path on my way to buildings on campus, and as such is one that holds within it various memories, many of which are rather indistinct. Yet all of these memories come together to create a nuanced sense of place, here, and that is most certainly worth noting. Sometimes there are awkward encounters, either because I am caught off guard by the sight of an acquaintance, or because some folks just walk remarkably slowly and I wish not to disturb them by passing too close, or because the geese do indeed weird me out. There are times when I pass through with friends, and others when I may be fortunate enough to witness the antics of fluffy dogs. The wonderful comes face to face with the awkward, the sweaty, and the anxious, creating a place that takes on all sorts of identities as my relation to it shifts and evolves, sometimes even from one day to the next. This complex concoction of memories spreads across my third, fourth, and fifth years of passing through campus as a student.",
            "time":["2022-2023", "2023-2024", "2024-2025"], "association":["Comfort", "Discomfort"], "color":"#228B22", "quirk":"Mellow Path", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30820035844734, 47.658370928190365],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Mellow Path", "memory":"I'll admit, adding this as a memory is a little cheeky of me. But it is certainly relevant to note that my first attempt at recollecting information in a given place happened right here, and that doing so has begun to influence how I perceive this space and my relation to it. By seeking to explore and–to an extent–complicate my relation to a space, my relation to it changes. Funny, isn't it, how exploring my relation to a space has begun to influence that relation… That's all to say that this memory of being mindful of myself in this space has influenced how I perceive this space, and has prompted me to more carefully consider who I am when in this space, who I want to be when in this space, and how I might strive for a care-driven relationship to the space as an entity of its own. This memory from the Summer of 2025 is a fond one, and I recall the joy that I felt when undergoing this careful and critical engagement with this space. Hmm… Perhaps a smidge of self-satisfaction is at play, too…",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Joy", "Comfort"], "color":"#32CD32", "quirk":"Mellow Path", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.3085808314811, 47.65833296261943],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Shared Office", "memory":"The sense of relief upon entering the room–oh, how splendid! This space brings to mind consistent memories of unlocking the door, entering the room, and gently closing the door behind me. Upon entry, I recall that I quite often felt more at ease near-instantaneously. There's a very tangible sense of relief that these memories invoke, as though I had the green light to relax a bit and let my hair down. These recurring instances are how most, if not all, of my interactions with the space begin, and they themselves begin from my first year of graduate studies (and my fifth year as a student here at UW).",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Comfort", "Belonging"], "color":"#80461B", "quirk":"Shared Office", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30741264257112, 47.65643069083474],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Shared Office", "memory":"This space may be quiet, but it is still very much one of conversation and collaboration! I can recall keen memories of various TA-, geography-, and department-related discussions with the other inhabitants of this space, as well as the casual and warm conversations that make this space feel like a home away from home. I am most thrilled to report that it is not uncommon for me to wind up with a bit of a post-conversational buzz at times. Put simply, this space contains various memories that revolve around building connections. Of these memories, the ones that I most closely associate with the space took place throughout the Winter and Spring of 2025.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Belonging", "Comfort", "Joy"], "color":"#FFF8DC", "quirk":"Shared Office", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30738633784752, 47.65640903525496],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Shared Office", "memory":"It is perhaps unsurprising that I have a strong association with a blended multitude of memories that revolve around the desk at which I often work. I can recall sitting at this desk when recollecting information for this project, and for the previous project, for example, but there are also less temporally distinct memories that I associate with this desk. The (sometimes awkward) times at which I eat some leftovers for lunch, for example, or preparing for class sections, seminars, meetings, and so on, are excellent examples. As one might surmise, a great deal of work is accomplished here, spanning the interpersonal to the academic and to the intellectual. These memories are vast and diverse, but they do often connect back to simple themes of hard work and preparation, as well as feelings of satisfaction and accomplishment. Given that I have been in this space since Fall 2024, I can safely say that these memories span the entirety from then to now, and quite likely to the future, too.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Belonging", "Comfort", "Confidence"], "color":"#FFD580", "quirk":"Shared Office", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30738926059458, 47.6563755675231],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Shared Office", "memory":"I have hosted in-person office hours here for two quarters now (Fall 2024 and Spring 2025), and there are indeed some prominent memories of such office hours that I associate with this space. I find that to offer particular details would be inconsiderate, so I might instead raise the implications of these memories. The memories of working with students during these times remind oneself of the responsibilities that are associated with this space and one’s identity within it. There is certainly a sense of accomplishment and confidence when questions are answered and concerns are addressed, but there is also the trepidation and self-doubt that lurks on the other side of the coin. What if there are questions and concerns that I am unable to address? What if a mistake that I make begins to snowball?",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Uncertainty", "Confidence"], "color":"#C41E3A", "quirk":"Shared Office", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30738926059458, 47.65639328573676],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Shared Office", "memory":"Ah, my very first moment in this space! I had just left Tea Club's 2024 Dawg Daze event (I had been brewing some tasty shou pu'er), and decided to stop by before making my way to a meeting. 'Discovering' the space for the first time was a magical moment, filled with excitement and promise–and, in real time, I felt my role and identity as a graduate student in the department beginning to crystallize. A note, welcoming me to the department, was neatly placed on my assigned desk, wonderfully punctuating my first interaction with this space. I remember taking in my surroundings, admiring the various texts and trinkets that others had placed in the room. The desk may have been the most prominent piece of this memory, and of the experience of discovery, but the other features of the space, that I would get to know better as time went on, contribute quite a bit to the sense of academic and intellectual self that began to develop that day.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Belonging", "Joy", "Comfort"], "color":"#FFD580", "quirk":"Shared Office", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.307391785914, 47.65638631749332],"type":"Point"}},
    
    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Smith 409", "memory":"This was my first time entering Smith Hall, and I hadn't a clue as to what I should expect. While the details of navigating the building for the first time have, unfortunately, evaded me, I most certainly remember entering Smith 409 for the first section of Geog 315 AC during the Fall of 2021. I was nervous, as is common for the first week of classes, but also so remarkably excited–this was my first in-person section! I remember entering the conference-style room and being caught off guard. Where should I sit? Is this a seminar-style class? Hmm… How often am I going to need to speak? I sat in the chairs away from the table, off to the right-side of the room. I could tell that I was among the youngest in the room, and this observation fueled my nervous energy. Fortunately, those who sat next to me made for quality conversation during the ice-breaking portion of the class (and, frankly, carried the conversation). Almost all of us in the room were Geography: Data Science majors, and quite a few were minoring in Informatics as well. The precise content of the introductory session eludes me, but I recall feeling quite excited about this course–while also feeling even more nervous about the seating arrangement, given that there were barely enough seats for everyone. As it so happens, we swapped 409 for 415C, which gave us much more space while also laying the foundation for my mental perception of Smith 409 as an elevated space for special occasions.",
            "time":["2021-2022"], "association":["Uncertainty", "Joy"], "color":"#E5E4E2", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30719344420385, 47.65673526754384],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Smith 409", "memory":"As an enjoyer of tea, I was quite thrilled when tea became a staple of our Critical GIS seminars during Spring 2025! We had started with black tea–likely a Jin Jun Mei–and after a few weeks had transitioned to Long Jing, a green tea. While I tend to be fond of all of the seminars I participate in, this one was particularly special. We had a wonderful cast of participants, wonderful tea to enjoy, and wonderful topics to explore. These discussions might have been the most at ease I have ever felt here in Smith 409, and it indeed felt as though we were creating our own unique classroom space! While some precise memories poke out above the rest, what primarily defines this particular association with this space is a collection of small memories and the exquisite vibes that persist throughout the entirety of that collection.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Joy", "Belonging", "Comfort"], "color":"#E4D00A", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30724315189514, 47.65671424381593],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Smith 409", "memory":"Contributing greatly to my perception of this space as one for formal endeavors (and one that is intimately tied to my role in the department) are my memories from the admitted graduate student day (sometime in March of 2024) and graduate student orientation (sometime in September of 2024), both hosted by the department. These two experiences, due to their surface-level similarities, seem to blend together when I consider them in relation to this space. Both offered a deluge of information that I really ought to have written down and have shaped the rather symbolic role of this space in my development as a geographer–not least because this is the space in which our formal introductions to the department took place for both days. Both days began with an uncomfortable overabundance of nervous energy and excitement, bubbling over at times into anxious feelings of trepidation and uncertainty. Yet, throughout each day I had developed a gradual sense of comfort and belonging, even if not yet complete at the time. In both cases, being around such wonderful people convinced me that while my uncertainties may persist, this is most certainly one of the better environments in which I might face them!",
            "time":["2023-2024", "2024-2025"], "association":["Uncertainty", "Belonging", "Comfort", "Confidence"], "color":"#DC143C", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30722705864153, 47.656752183629266],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Smith 409", "memory":"During Winter of 2025, I had taken part in Geog 511, a course that walked us through the development of a research proposal. There was certainly the uncertainty of developing a research project for an MA thesis (and the anxieties of 'getting it right'), but also the excitement and promise of all sorts of emerging ideas and the wonderful opportunities to share thoughts with others and engage with each others’ research directions. The opportunity to have what was really a remarkable amount of dedicated time to discuss each of our proposals and their development throughout the quarter had given me a lot of confidence in my work, and thus in my identity as a geographer. This was a quarter when my identity as a researcher really began to take tangible shape, as I initially planned out this very research project and explored themes of care, place, and GIS, and how they might all come together in a set of projects. The following quarter, and in the same room, I had participated in Geog 525, a qualitative methods course that had provided me with further avenues to explore my identity and approach as a researcher. Putting myself aside, for a moment, this was also a moment of intellectual community building as those of us in the course were able to explore each other’s research and support the development of each other’s research. Put simply, this is a memory that links to my sense of place in the geographic discipline and in the department–rather symbolic, given the associations of this space with more tangible academic milestones. Ah, and I must not forget the chalkboard exercises, where the literature review processes quite helpfully took visual form!",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Uncertainty", "Belonging", "Confidence", "Joy"], "color":"#E5E4E2", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30720560097011, 47.6567377303703],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Savery 117", "memory":"Marking a drastic shift in my relation to this space was my first experience leading a lab section in the Fall of 2024. No longer was I a student, but a graduate student who was now responsible for teaching and supporting those of whom I was so recently one of. I had arrived early, and I distinctly recall the foreboding emptiness of the classroom, knowing that it was soon to be full of students that hadn't worked with me before. That was a most intimidating day, and it indeed caught me underprepared. I did not know how to set up the projector (while I was right to assume that I could figure out the logic for turning the screen on, I did not realize the necessary remote would not be present in the room, and did not account for the anxieties of figuring things out the day-of), and was similarly caught off guard by changes in Mapbox's sign-up procedures, which had tripped up students and myself much more than I had expected. I had spent too much time going over the course housekeeping and icebreakers, too, making for a tight squeeze when it came to covering the lab content for the day. It was embarrassing; I did not prepare the quick solutions as I should have, and I felt visibly flustered. All that said, this is also a memory that contains within it the excitement of facing a new challenge, and the promise of personal growth–even if the challenge had come sooner (and was less exciting) than I had hoped, and the personal growth started with an uncomfortable lesson on being fully prepared.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Discomfort", "Uncertainty"], "color":"#343434", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30787347101376, 47.65742967566633],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Savery 117", "memory":"Roughly midway through my second quarter as a TA, during the Winter of 2025, something had finally clicked. As we had settled into lab sessions for the quarter, our lab sessions became uniquely interactive. Labs walkthroughs became a communal process, thanks in no small part to engaged students who asked key questions along the way and did not shy away from requesting clarification. I recall pausing and wandering around the room to answer questions after natural break points, providing a clear opportunity for students to raise questions and catch up without interrupting the lab demonstration. I felt well-prepared for our sessions–I had the lab steps down to a T–while also feeling flexible and relaxed enough to thoughtfully respond to unanticipated questions or concerns, or to shift gears when necessary. Having nearly two hours set aside for these labs certainly helped, as I was able to comfortably cover all of the lab content within the allotted time. Most important, however, was the brilliant cast of students who made these sessions a joy and a success. This space really is a reminder that it is indeed possible to set up a wonderful and dynamic learning environment in my role as a TA, even if there are still plenty of mistakes to be made and lessons to be learned ahead.",
            "time":["2024-2025"], "association":["Confidence", "Joy", "Belonging"], "color":"#F4BB44", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.3078863516045, 47.65739899719934],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Geog 315", "memory":"I must confess that this vague memory of the near-unbearable squeakiness of wet shoes persists in my imagination of this space, even if enough time has passed that I am no longer certain of the reliability of such a memory. Nevertheless, the memory of shoes squeaking all the way through the building, up to and including the Gowen 201 classroom (home of Geog 315), haunts me much the same as the squeaking itself. Oh, the annoyance! Oh, the embarrassment (if I was the culprit)! Oh, the smugness (if I had the foresight to use the doormat but someone else did not)! What is perhaps most interesting, however, is how this memory reveals a seeming discomfort with making such noises in the building…",
            "time":["2021-2022"], "association":["Discomfort"], "color":"#B6D0E2", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30795477822991, 47.656417296526286],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Geog 315", "memory":"It is perhaps a geographic cliche, but the lecture exercise of reading the landscape in Geog 315 had indeed cemented my interest in geography. I was most certainly interested in geography–I was here in this course, and in the major!–but this was the fabled lightbulb moment when I finally realized that geography had the promise to fulfill the nuanced and open-ended question that had followed me since my earliest days in school: why is the world the way it is? This lecture had, rather auspiciously, demonstrated to me that geographers had the tools to answer that question in all sorts of unique and unexpected ways, while still leaving room for the recognition that no single explanation will ever be enough.",
            "time":["2021-2022"], "association":["Joy", "Belonging", "Confidence"], "color":"#355E3B", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.3078768203301, 47.65639036806449],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Geog 315", "memory":"This space also holds within it my first memories of being put on the spot during lectures (in this case, for Geog 315)–memories of which I am surprisingly fond! While I struggle to recall the particularities of the content that I was prompted to engage with, I do recall that I could anticipate being put on the spot based upon eye contact. This gave my brain a few extra instances to process and prepare information, which did indeed come in handy at times. These memories serve as proof that I can indeed engage with ideas on the spot, even if I may be unprepared or not entirely confident. The vaguest sense of regret and embarrassment lingers, but that has most to do with the involuntary retrofit of my responses after the fact. It is interesting, though, that the recollection of being put on the spot is so closely linked to this space, when I have had similar experiences in other spaces… Might this be related to the role of this space as my first in-person classroom?",
            "time":["2021-2022"], "association":["Confidence", "Uncertainty"], "color":"#5C4033", "quirk":"", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30786682572764, 47.6563836359469],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Tea Club (First Year)", "memory":"This memory from October of 2022 contains within itself such immense promise! This was our very first meeting as Tea Club, and while hosting tea here in the HUB was certainly a bit of a learning curve, it was indeed quite the (relative) success. We had yet to advertise the club beyond the default RSO directory, but, somehow, a new member had already found us! Truth be told, we might not have had the best grasp on how to manage tea here in this space. It took us some time to find a suitable outlet for the kettle, and we wandered around for a bit before settling on one of the booths near the dining services. Unfortunately, I do not recall the teas that we had brewed that day, but it was certainly an auspicious–if occasionally awkward–launch for the club.",
            "time":["2022-2023"], "association":["Joy", "Uncertainty"], "color":"#FFE7B8", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30497134263527, 47.655220206315704],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Tea Club (First Year)", "memory":"Back in early Spring of 2023, we hosted a Tea Club meeting with a special twist: tea and snack pairings, courtesy of TeaJTea! While it was indeed a fun time, the lack of vegan options did dampen my spirits considerably. I recall, too, a sense of disappointment from new guests who seemed to be caught off guard by the rather annoyingly boisterous energy that some of the regulars had brought with them (and quite reasonably so). This was a moment when I realized that the image of Tea Club and the actual atmosphere of our meetings were often in tension, as the quiet and introspective associations that people may have with tea drinking were countered by the wild energy of some who may have over-relied on caffeine. Thus, this event marked a promising growth of Tea Club that materialized less in additional attendance and more in our ties to local tea vendors. All that said, we did manage to secure a wonderful booth near an outlet that fit the needs of the club quite well–a minor victory in itself.",
            "time":["2022-2023"], "association":["Joy", "Uncertainty"], "color":"#FFE7B8", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.3049101636211, 47.6551055360115],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Tea Club", "memory":"In the past few years, TeaJTea (a local tea vendor) has hosted a handful of events with Tea Club, most of which took place in this space. Our first meeting with them was in April of 2023, with only three club officers. I had been greatly anticipating this meeting, and it most certainly did not disappoint! This was a wonderful opportunity to get to know them, their business, their experience in the tea industry, and their tastes in tea. It may have been disheartening to see how few of us were able to make it, but fewer numbers allowed for us all to engage more deeply in conversation and with the teas and snacks at hand. Teas that came from their personal collection, to boot! As a club hosting tea professionals, we had felt a bit clumsy; the space was not exactly ideal for tea brewing nor was it particularly comfortable (the glare from the sun outside was rather potent…). After our meeting, they had offered to us a box full of tea and snacks to share at our club tea times, for which we were, and very much still are, immensely grateful. Our next event with them was in November of 2023, where we sampled some of their tea and pastry pairings in a more organized setting. We had moved further down by the windows this time, which proved to be a much improved experience and much better suited to a full group. This event was designed for the club members who were new to tea, and there was a lot of excitement among everyone. I was working on my graduate school application at the time, so my mind was largely elsewhere, but I had certainly enjoyed the event. The next event of theirs in this space that I had attended was two days short of a year later, in the same area as the last, and this time the teas and pastries were themed for the holidays. These were all herbal teas and not, admittedly, to my particular tastes, but this event was similarly a hit among attendees. Vegan pastries were present, which had lifted my spirits considerably! My friend and I went for dinner and brewed some of our own tea after, putting a nice little bow on this particular day of tea.",
            "time":["2022-2023", "2023-2024", "2024-2025"], "association":["Joy", "Comfort"], "color":"#CC7722", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30475322614988, 47.655196913930524],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Tea Club (First Year)", "memory":"There are a few notable early Tea Club meetings that, while not quite prominent in my memories, are still present in my perception of this space. The first such meeting was an exquisite tea time with a few friends. One of us brought snacks, and we had a most wonderful and thoughtful conversation. Another meeting, later in the year, featured what was, at the time, a remarkable number of new members–including a future officer who would later bring immense tea (and tea knowledge) to the figurative and literal table. My other recollections of tea times in this space have since blended together, but these two remain distinct.",
            "time":["2022-2023"], "association":["Joy", "Comfort", "Belonging"], "color":"#B87333", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30493410323533, 47.655238123528],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Tea Club (Contemporary)", "memory":"In the second year of Tea Club, we had shifted our meeting space to this area, having found it to be more suitable for brewing tea, and for a larger number of attendees. This first year of hosting tea in this space was altogether quite splendid, but a few memories rise above the rest. These memories weave in and out of each other, making distinct recollection rather difficult, and tend to be steeped in nostalgia. The most prominent and distinct of these memories brings me back to the early afternoon of a Tuesday in the February of 2024. This was a new time of the day for club tea brewing, and only a few of us had been able to attend the session–oh, but what a wonderful session it was! This was a most splendid moment, and it would not be much of a stretch to claim that it strengthened the fabric of the club leadership. Those of us who did attend either were or promptly became officers, and we shared a great deal of tea and stories. I recall beginning this particular tea session concerned about attendance, or the worrying lack thereof; I left knowing that this would be a tea memory that we would cherish for a long while. There were similarly splendid tea times throughout the entire academic year, often with a similar mix of familiar faces and passionate tea drinkers. Wonderful conversation and wonderful tea–what more could one ask for? These memories are among my most treasured of those from this campus.",
            "time":["2023-2024"], "association":["Joy", "Belonging", "Comfort"], "color":"#96DED1", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30521871865228, 47.65482781781965],"type":"Point"}},

    {"type":"Feature","properties":
        {"space":"Tea Club (Contemporary)", "memory":"Oh, goodness–this was quite the wild tea day! In early March of 2024, Tea Club had invited Crimson Lotus, a local tea vendor, to host an event on campus. I can still recall the dizzying buzz of anticipation! A few of the other officers and I arrived early to help set up, which proved to be simpler than we had presumed. Tables had to be moved, and we created a crescent shape around the brewing station. A brewing station, I might add, that was entirely decked out with all of the necessary extension cords, filtered water, tea wares–everything that we needed, Crimson Lotus had provided! As the event unfolded, we were treated to various teas of theirs and incredible stories from the tea industry. I ended up a bit too tea tipsy and had to take a brief snack break to reset. PNW Love, one of their most popular teas, seemed to be the consensus favorite of the day, inspiring at least a few purchases. It was certainly a joyful experience, but not without its tension: my tastes do not always align with the teas offered by Crimson Lotus, and there were a few moments here and there where this became apparent. That being said, this was a most brilliant tea time! A few friends and I made plans for a tea party later that evening, but that is a story for another space…",
            "time":["2023-2024"], "association":["Discomfort", "Joy", "Belonging"], "color":"#FAF9F6", "quirk":"Tea", "value":""},
        "geometry":{"coordinates":[-122.30534373663782, 47.65473823099284],"type":"Point"}}
]}